SIMPLE: mend
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mend
<hw>Mend</hw> <pr>(m⟦ecr⟧nd)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mended</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Abbrev. fr. <ets>amend</ets>.
See <er>Amend</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To repair, as anything that is torn, broken,
defaced, decayed, or the like; to restore from partial decay, injury, or
defacement; to patch up; to put in shape or order again; to re-create;
<as>as, to <ex>mend</ex> a garment or a machine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To alter for the better; to set right; to reform;
hence, to quicken; <as>as, to <ex>mend</ex> one's manners or
pace</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The best service they could do the state was to <qex>mend</qex>
the lives of the persons who composed it.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To help, to advance, to further; to add
to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though in some lands the grass is but short, yet it
<qex>mends</qex> garden herbs and fruit.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>mend</qex> the jewel by the wearing it.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To improve; help; better; emend; amend; correct;
rectify; reform.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mend
<hw>Mend</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow better; to advance to a
better state; to become improved; to recover; to heal.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>on the mend</b></col> <pos>pred. a.</pos> <cd>recovering
from an illness or injury.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendable</ent>⟦br⟧
